{meta: title Oklahoma Morning}
{meta: artist Charlie Pride}
{meta: composer Jim Chesnut}

{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[C]On an early autumn day
[G7]Freshness of the breeze brought the [C]morning
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
And the sun came rising up
[F]Shining down on leaves that [G7]fell like golden [C]snow
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
And the mystery of it all
[G7]Made the problems of the day seem [C]unimportant
[F]That Oklahoma morning
[G7]Puts Oklahoma sunshine in my soul
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
[C]There ain't nothing like an [F]Oklahoma [C]morning
[F]Nothing like it when you're feeling [G7]low
[F]It warms up your [G7]mind and your [C]body
[F]It puts Oklahoma [G7]sunshine in your [C]soul
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 5}
Our campfire came to life
[G7]The crackling of the fire and smell of [C]coffee
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 6}
Turned back the time
[F]To a day when a man [G7]could listen for a [C]while
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 7}
To the sound of mother nature
[G7]Without the sound of industry in the [C]background
[F]That Oklahoma morning
[G7]Puts Oklahoma sunshine in my smi-le
{end_of_verse}

